{"title_page": "That's Entertainment (Philippine TV program)", "text_new": "{{short description|Philippine television show}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2018}}\n{{about||the Emirati series|That's Entertainment (Emirati TV program)|other uses|That's Entertainment (disambiguation){{!}}That's Entertainment}}\n{{distinguish|Nuts Entertainment}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name = That's Entertainment\n| image = That's Entertainment title card.jpg\n| caption = Title card\n| genre = [[Variety show]]\n| picture_format = [[480i]] ([[SDTV]])\n| runtime = 60 minutes\n| executive_producer = Lenny C. Parto\n| director = Bud Daliwan\n| company = GMA Productions Inc.\n| presenter = {{plain list|\n* [[German Moreno]]\n* [[Ike Lozada]]}}\n| language = [[Tagalog language|Tagalog]]\n| country = [[Philippines]]\n| network = [[GMA Network]]\n| location = {{plainlist|\n* GMA Building, [[Quezon City]], Philippines {{small|(1986-1987)}}\n* [[GMA Broadway Centrum]], Quezon City, Philippines {{small|(1987-1996)}}}}\n| camera = [[Multiple-camera setup]]\n| first_aired = {{start date|1986|1|6}}\n| last_aired = {{end date|1996|5|3}}\n| num_episodes = 3,200\n}}\n\n'''''That's Entertainment''''' is a [[Philippine television]] [[variety show]] broadcast by [[GMA Network]]. Originally hosted by [[German Moreno]] and [[Ike Lozada]], it premiered on January 6, 1986. The show concluded on May 3, 1996 with a total of 3,200 episodes.\n\n==Overview==\n{{multiple image\n|direction = vertical\n|align = right\n|image1 = Germsnorajf.jpg\n|caption1 = German Moreno serves as a host.\n|width1 = 150\n}}\n\nThe show was created by [[German Moreno]] who initially wanted teenaged celebrity siblings to star in the show and name it as ''Brothers and Sisters''. After watching the American film ''[[That's Entertainment!]]'', Moreno decided to change the title of the show. Premiering on January 6, 1986 on [[GMA Network]], the show featured sixteen teenagers (divided into 4 from Monday to Thursday and gathered all together on Friday). The show later joined the network's Saturday afternoon line up. The show first aired from the GMA building in EDSA and eventually moved to [[GMA Broadway Centrum]] in 1987 to accommodate a wider studio audience.<ref name=thats-history>{{cite web|author1=Young, Rica |author2=Dimaculangan, Jocelyn |title=That's Entertainment |url=https://www.pep.ph/peptionary/147046/that-s-entertainment-cast-a4495-a2670-20191028-lfrm2 |publisher=[[Philippine Entertainment Portal]] |date=October 28, 2019|accessdate=April 24, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe cast members were separated into five groups; Monday, Tuesday, Wednesday, Thursday and Friday. During the Saturday broadcast, all five groups performed together. The show also featured dance groups such as the Manoeuvres, Streetboys, Abztract Dancers, Kids at Work, and Universal Motion Dancers.\n\nThe final episode, \"That's The Reunion\" aired on May 3, 1996, which featured former cast members of the show.<ref name=thats-history/>\n\n==Cast==\n<!-- Please take note of the correct day group for the members of That's Entertainment based on media sources, familiarity, and their social media accounts. You may also watch YouTube videos for confirmation. Each group is arranged alphabetically.-->\nAccording to day groups:\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:95%;\"\n|-\n! Monday<ref>{{cite news|title=\u2018That\u2019s Entertainment Monday Group\u2019 Nasaan na kaya sila?|trans-title=That's Entertainment Monday Group, where are they now|language=tl|url=https://www.abante.com.ph/thats-entertainment-monday-group-nasaan-na-kaya-sila.htm|publisher=[[Abante]]|date=7 April 2018|accessdate=24 April 2020}}</ref>\n! Tuesday<ref>{{cite news|author=Sun, Cherry|title='That's Entertainment' Tuesday group, reunited!|url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/entertainment/showbiznews/news/35444/look-thats-entertainment-tuesday-group-reunited/story|publisher=[[Abante]]|date=23 November 2017|accessdate=24 April 2020}}</ref>\n! Wednesday\n! Thursday\n! Fri